        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>local citation</strong> is any online mention of a business's <strong>name, address, and phone number (NAP)</strong> on websites, directories, or social platforms. Citations act as third-party validation that helps Google verify business legitimacy and are one of the <strong>top 5 factors for Local Pack ranking</strong> (Moz, Whitespark).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking factor rank</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Top 5 (Local Pack)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Typical target</div>
            <div class="tms-value">80-150 citations</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Impact timeline</div>
            <div class="tms-value">4-8 weeks</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every mention of your business online with a matching name, address, and phone number tells Google the same story: this business is real, located here, and reachable at this number. The stronger and more consistent that story, the higher you rank in the Local Pack.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a local citation?</h2>
        <p>A local citation is a reference to a business on a third-party site that includes the business's NAP data — often with additional attributes like website URL, hours, and categories. Citations exist on structured business directories (Yelp, YellowPages) and on unstructured mentions (blog posts, news articles).</p>
        <p>Citations serve four distinct purposes for Google:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Legitimacy verification</strong> — a business that appears on many trusted directories is more likely to be real</li>
          <li><strong>NAP consistency scoring</strong> — matching data across dozens of listings raises Google's confidence</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence signal</strong> — the number and authority of directory mentions correlates with Local Pack ranking</li>
          <li><strong>Referral traffic</strong> — high-DA directories drive direct clicks from customers researching businesses</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The Whitespark finding</div>
          <p>Whitespark's Local Search Ranking Factors Study consistently ranks citation signals among the <strong>top 5 factors for Local Pack ranking</strong>. Businesses with more consistent citations on authoritative directories outrank those with fewer or inconsistent ones — even when Google Business Profile completeness is equivalent.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why local citations matter for local SEO</h2>
        <p>Citations are one of the few local ranking factors that a small business can control directly. Three reasons they deserve consistent effort:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Direct Local Pack impact.</strong> The Local Pack (the map + 3 businesses) captures ~44% of local search clicks. Citations directly influence which three businesses show.</li>
          <li><strong>Data aggregator leverage.</strong> Submitting to the four major US aggregators (Data Axle, Localeze, Foursquare, Neustar) propagates your NAP to hundreds of secondary directories automatically.</li>
          <li><strong>Direct referral traffic.</strong> High-authority directories — Yelp, BBB, industry-specific sites — send real customer visits, not just SEO signal.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How citations actually work</h2>
        <p>Three systems interact whenever Google evaluates citations for local ranking: crawl-based discovery, aggregator distribution, and consistency scoring.</p>

        <h3>1. Crawler discovery</h3>
        <p>Googlebot crawls major directories and business databases, extracting NAP data and matching it back to Google Business Profile listings. Any mismatch between GBP and directory data creates a confidence penalty.</p>

        <h3>2. Data aggregator layer</h3>
        <p>Four large aggregators feed hundreds of secondary directories. Fixing NAP at the aggregator level cascades down cleanly. Ignoring aggregators means bad data multiplies.</p>

        <h3>3. Quality and consistency scoring</h3>
        <p>Not all citations count equally. A citation on a Chamber of Commerce site outweighs a citation on a low-quality auto-generated aggregator. Consistency across those citations — exact match on business name, address format, and phone — raises Google's confidence in the underlying data.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
